      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why Z-Containing Words Dominate Scrabble Scoring</h2>
      <p>Z is the most rewarding tile in Scrabble when you consider value-to-playability ratio. Worth 10 points (tied with Q), Z doesn't require a companion letter the way Q needs U. This makes Z far more flexible and reliable as a scoring weapon. You can place Z at the start of words (ZIGZAG, ZAP), in the middle (FIZZY, BUZZER, FROZEN), or at the end (WALTZ, JAZZ, QUIZ).</p>
      <p>The two-letter Z words — ZA and ZO — are particularly powerful for parallel plays, each scoring 11 points from just two tiles. Words with double or triple Z like PIZZAZZ (45 pts), FIZZY (29 pts), and ZIGZAG (26 pts) are among the highest-scoring plays in the game. When you draw Z, your priority should be finding a premium square to land it on. Z on a double letter square gives you 20 points from one tile; on a triple letter square, that's 30 points before counting the rest of the word.</p>

